        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cron): prevent one-shot at jobs from re-triggering after completion",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nFixes #56488\n\n`kind: \"at\"` cron jobs with `deleteAfterRun: true` fire repeatedly instead of once. The reporter observed a one-shot Sparkle insight job firing 7+ times overnight, each spawning an isolated agent session that generated content and posted to Discord.\n\n## Root Cause\n\n`isRunnableJob` has a `skipAtIfAlreadyRan` guard (line 753) that prevents completed one-shot jobs from re-triggering. But this guard is only enabled when called from `runMissedJobs` (the startup catch-up path, line 873).\n\nThe normal `onTimer` tick (line 595) and `runDueJobs` (line 1006) call `collectRunnableJobs` WITHOUT `skipAtIfAlreadyRan`. So completed \"at\" jobs with past-due `nextRunAtMs` are treated as runnable on every scheduler tick, because `nowMs >= nextRunAtMs` is always true for a past timestamp.\n\n```\nonTimer tick:\n  collectRunnableJobs(state, now)  ← no skipAtIfAlreadyRan\n  → isRunnableJob:\n    → skipAtIfAlreadyRan? NO (not passed)\n    → nowMs >= nextRunAtMs? YES (past timestamp)\n    → return true  ← re-triggers!\n\nrunMissedJobs (startup):\n  collectRunnableJobs(state, now, { skipAtIfAlreadyRan: true })\n  → isRunnableJob:\n    → skipAtIfAlreadyRan? YES\n    → lastStatus === \"ok\"? YES\n    → return false  ← correctly skipped\n```\n\n## Fix\n\nPass `skipAtIfAlreadyRan: true` in both `onTimer` and `runDueJobs`, matching the startup catch-up path behavior. The guard implementation already handles all edge cases (error retries with `nextRun > lastRun`).",
